ructures exposed to environmental stresses, such as aging infrastructure, seismic activity, and extreme weather conditions. They enable proactive maintenance and ensure the safety and longevity of these assets.</p><p>Moreover, fiber optic sensing solutions are being integrated into the design phase of new civil engineering projects, ensuring that structures are built with optimal durability and resilience. The technology supports the development of smart cities by enabling continuous monitoring of the physical infrastructure, offering insights into potential risks, and contributing to sustainable urban planning. As the demand for more resilient infrastructure increases globally, fiber optic sensing technologies are expected to see significant growth in the civil and engineering sectors.</p><h3>Aerospace</h3><p>The aerospace industry has been quick to adopt fiber optic sensing solutions, primarily for monitoring the health and performance of aircraft and spacecraft. These sensors are used to measure parameters such as strain, temperature, pressure, and vibration within aircraft components, allowing for early detection of potential failure points. In aircraft, fiber optic sensors are embedded in critical areas like wings, fuselage, and engines to monitor structural integrity and performance. Their lightweight and non-electromagnetic properties make them particularly well-suited for aerospace applications, where reducing weight and ensuring safety are of paramount importance.</p><p>Furthermore, fiber optic sensors are increasingly used in space exploration and satellite systems to monitor environmental conditions and ensure operational safety. As the demand for advanced aerospace technologies increases, the need for real-time monitoring and predictive maintenance systems is expected to drive further adoption of fiber optic sensing solutions. Their ability to operate in extreme conditions and their durability make them essential for next-generation aerospace application